06717nam a22008055i 9780812293883DE-B159720200826040535.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200826t20172017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)992454263  a97808122938837 a10.9783/97808122938832doi  a(DE-B1597)481222  a(OCoLC)982452934  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a33822300aGreen Capitalism? :bBusiness and the Environment in the Twentieth Century /cHartmut Berghoff, Adam Rome. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b6 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHagley Perspectives on Business and Culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. The Ecology of Commerce: Environmental History and the Challenge of Building a Sustainable Economy -- tChapter 2. Shades of Green: A Business- History Perspective on Eco- Capitalism -- tChapter 3. The Role of Businesses in Constructing Systems of Environmental Governance -- tChapter 4. Business Leadership in the Movement to Regulate Industrial Air Pollution in Late Nineteenth- and Early Twentieth-Century America -- tChapter 5. “Constructive and Not Destructive Development”: Permanent Uses of Resources in the American South -- tChapter 6. Utilities as Conservationists? Th e Paradox of Electrification During the Progressive Era in North America -- tChapter 7. Plastic Six- Pack Rings: The Business and Politics of an Environmental Problem -- tChapter 8. The Rise and Fall of an Ecostar: Green Technology Innovation and Marketing as Regulatory Obstruction -- tChapter 9. Dilemmas of Going Green: Environmental Strategies in the Swedish Mining Company Boliden, 1960–2000 -- tChapter 10. Private Companies and the Recycling of Household Waste in West Germany, 1965–1990 -- tChapter 11. Kill-a-Watt: The Greening of Consolidated Edison in the 1970s -- tChapter 12. Entrepreneurship, Policy, and the Geography of Wind Energy -- tChapter 13. Driving Change: The Winding Road to Greener Automobiles -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgments 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt a time when the human impact on the environment is more devastating than ever, business initiatives frame the quest to "green" capitalism as the key to humanity's long-term survival. Indeed, even before the rise of the environmental movement in the 1970s, businesses sometimes had reasons to protect parts of nature, limit their production of wastes, and support broader environmental reforms. In the last thirty years, especially, many businesses have worked hard to reduce their direct and indirect environmental footprint. But are these efforts exceptional, or can capitalism truly be environmentally conscious?Green Capitalism? offers a critical, historically informed perspective on building a more sustainable economy. Written by scholars of business history and environmental history, the essays in this volume consider the nature of capitalism through historical overviews of twentieth-century businesses and a wide range of focused case studies. Beginning early in the century, contributors explore the response of business leaders to environmental challenges in an era long before the formation of the modern regulatory state. Moving on to midcentury environmental initiatives, scholars analyze failed business efforts to green products and packaging—such as the infamous six-pack ring—in the 1960s and 1970s. The last section contains case studies of businesses that successfully managed greening initiatives, from the first effort by an electric utility to promote conservation, to the environmental overhaul of a Swedish mining company, to the problem of household waste in pre-1990 West Germany. Ranging in geographic scope from Europe to the United States, Green Capitalism? raises questions about capitalism in different historical, sociocultural, and political contexts.Contributors: Hartmut Berghoff, Ann-Kristin Bergquist, Brian C. Black, William D. Bryan, Julie Cohn, Leif Fredrickson, Hugh S. Gorman, Geoffrey Jones, David Kinkela, Roman Köster, Joseph A. Pratt, Adam Rome, Christine Meisner Rosen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Aug 2020) 0aBusiness enterprisesxEnvironmental aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aCapitalismxEnvironmental aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aEnvironmental policyxEconomic aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aEnvironmentalismxEconomic aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 4aAmerican History. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aBerghoff, Hartmut, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRome, Adam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2017z9783110547764oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package 2017z978311055030640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229388340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812293883423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812293883.jpg  a978-3-11-055030-6  Penn Press eBook Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DEGb2017  aZDB-23-DGGb2017